Stocks in South Africa Rise for 7th Day, BHP Billiton, Datatec Are Active

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-07-04T15:44:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-04/south-african-stocks-datatec-gold-fields-harmony-steinhoff-shares-move.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
rose for a seventh day to its highest level in more than a
month, gaining 152.32, or 0.5 percent, to 32,077.79 by the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  AVI Ltd. (AVI)  , a producer and distributor of consumer
goods including food and cosmetics, reached the highest price
since at least August 1990, adding 1.03 rand, or 3.3 percent, to
32.25 rand. The group bought back 8.98 million of its own shares
for 269 million rand ($40 million).  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, closed at its highest since May 31, rising 2.30 rand,
or 0.9 percent, to 267.70 rand. Copper advanced to a two-month
high in  London  on speculation  China , the world’s biggest
consumer of the metal, may refrain from tightening monetary
policy further after figures indicated weaker growth. Lead,
nickel, tin and zinc also increased.  Datatec Ltd. (DTC)  , a Johannesburg-based computer
services company, rallied 81 cents, or 2.2 percent, to 38.43
rand. The group said its Logicalis unit agreed to buy Netarx LLC
for as much as $34 million.  Exxaro Resources Ltd. (EXX)  , the biggest seller of coal
to South African power utility Eskom Holdings SOC Ltd., fell for
a second day, retreating 2.25 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 175 rand.
Coal prices at Richards Bay,  South Africa , the biggest terminal
in Africa to ship the fuel, fell 0.5 percent last week to an
average $117.06 a metric ton, the third consecutive weekly
decline, according to researcher IHS McCloskey.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , Africa’s second-biggest producer
of the metal, gained for the first day in three, adding 2.94
rand, or 3.1 percent, to 98.74 rand. Spot gold increased as much
as 0.6 percent to $1,496.90 an ounce.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. Ltd. (HAR SJ), the third-largest
producer, gained 70 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 86.50 rand.  Steinhoff International Holdings Ltd. (SHF)   closed at
its highest since June 15, rising 53 cents, or 2.3 percent, to
23.47 rand. The group said its European unit successfully
completed a 1.26 billion-euro ($2 billion) syndicated loan
facility on June 29.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
